01:13.006 --> 01:16.377
Yield, people!
Why won't you yield?

01:32.994 --> 01:34.695
Auggie! Wait up.

01:34.763 --> 01:36.529
Twenty minutes late, Walker?

01:36.597 --> 01:37.864
If I didn't know you
any better,

01:37.932 --> 01:39.365
I'd say you
were getting cocky.

01:39.433 --> 01:41.300
Actually, I had to drive
all the way to Capitol Hill

01:41.368 --> 01:42.668
to lose a tail.

01:42.736 --> 01:45.003
Seeing as I'm
only 20 minutes late,

01:45.071 --> 01:46.472
I have good reason
to be cocky.

01:46.540 --> 01:48.541
Probably another round
of random surveillance checks.

01:48.608 --> 01:49.909
Was it C.I.C.?

01:49.977 --> 01:51.445
Worse.
My sister.

01:51.512 --> 01:52.746
Ouch.

01:52.814 --> 01:54.281
If I can't fool
my sister,

01:54.349 --> 01:56.149
how am I gonna fare against
F.S.B. counter-intelligence?

01:56.217 --> 01:58.519
Nah, what you're going through
is completely normal.

01:58.586 --> 01:59.854
When I first joined
the agency,

01:59.922 --> 02:01.990
my brother tailed me,
he checked emails,

02:02.058 --> 02:03.324
eavesdropped
on phone calls.

02:03.392 --> 02:04.692
After a while,
he just stopped.

02:04.760 --> 02:07.228
- Why'd he lose interest?
- I bought him an Xbox.

02:07.296 --> 02:09.463
I don't think that's
gonna work with my sister.

02:09.531 --> 02:10.798
Meh.

02:10.866 --> 02:12.700
What's Arthur doing
in the D.P.D.?

02:12.768 --> 02:14.402
If Arthur's in here,

02:14.469 --> 02:16.737
it's either bad news
or really bad news.

02:16.805 --> 02:19.206
He's walking with Joan
up to her office.

02:19.274 --> 02:21.975
- Huh.
- Morning.

02:22.043 --> 02:25.478
I'm afraid I'm here
under unfortunate circumstances.

02:25.546 --> 02:27.647
Two days ago,
an active C.I.A. case officer,

02:27.714 --> 02:30.283
codename Moonlight,
was killed in the line of duty.

02:30.351 --> 02:32.486
The loss of life
for any public servant

02:32.553 --> 02:33.920
is tragic,

02:33.988 --> 02:36.657
but at the agency,
it is the rarest of events.

02:36.724 --> 02:38.459
In the last 65 years,

02:38.526 --> 02:42.263
the U.S. Armed Forces
have lost 101,712 lives,

02:42.331 --> 02:45.367
law enforcement,
10,635,

02:45.434 --> 02:48.437
C.I.A., 103.

02:48.505 --> 02:51.173
The number lost
on U.S. soil, 4.

02:51.241 --> 02:53.643
Those with "Need to know"
will be looped in further.

02:53.711 --> 02:56.180
Until then,
all I can say is

02:56.247 --> 02:59.083
we've lost
a good operative.

03:03.088 --> 03:05.957
I've never seen it
so quiet in here.

03:06.025 --> 03:07.259
If they can get
to one of us,

03:07.326 --> 03:08.527
it means they
can get to any of us.

03:08.594 --> 03:11.564
Annie...
A word?

03:18.740 --> 03:22.109
I have something
very difficult to tell you.

03:22.177 --> 03:23.944
The operative
who was killed,

03:24.012 --> 03:26.547
he was someone
you knew.

03:26.614 --> 03:27.981
That's impossible.

03:28.049 --> 03:31.752
Every covert operative I know
is in that bullpen.

03:33.454 --> 03:35.322
Mark Ramsay?
Why do you have

03:35.390 --> 03:38.625
a photo of my Georgetown
language professor?

03:38.693 --> 03:40.560
Was he somehow associated
with Moonlight?

03:40.628 --> 03:43.063
Annie,
he <i>was</i> Moonlight.

03:43.130 --> 03:46.252
And you're the only one
who can help us find his killer.

